#This command installs all the libraries needed to give your JARVIS ears and a voice:

#pip install openai-whisper elevenlabs sounddevice soundfile numpy pyaudio

#Let's break down each package.

1. openai-whisper
pip install openai-whisper
What it does:

Converts speech → text.

Example:

You say:

"Open Chrome"

Whisper converts it to:

"Open Chrome"
Used for:
Voice assistants
Meeting transcription
Speech recognition
Subtitle generation
In JARVIS:
Your voice
      ↓
   Whisper
      ↓
Text command
2. elevenlabs
pip install elevenlabs
What it does:

Converts text → realistic speech.

Example:

"Good morning, Srushti."

becomes spoken audio.

Why people love it:

The voices sound very natural.

In JARVIS:
Gemini's reply
      ↓
   ElevenLabs
      ↓
Spoken response
3. sounddevice
pip install sounddevice
What it does:

Records audio from your microphone and plays audio.

Example:

import sounddevice as sd

Record:

recording = sd.rec(...)
In JARVIS:
Microphone
      ↓
 sounddevice
      ↓
Audio file
4. soundfile
pip install soundfile
What it does:

Reads and writes audio files.

Example:

import soundfile as sf

sf.write("audio.wav", recording, 16000)

Whisper likes .wav files.

5. numpy
pip install numpy
What it does:

Performs numerical computations.

Audio recordings are actually arrays:

[0.1, 0.3, -0.2, ...]

These are stored as NumPy arrays.

Nearly every AI and audio library depends on NumPy.

6. pyaudio
pip install pyaudio
What it does:

Provides access to your microphone and speakers.

Used by:

speech_recognition
Audio streaming
Voice assistants
How everything works together
You speak
    ↓
Microphone
    ↓
sounddevice / pyaudio
    ↓
Audio file (.wav)
    ↓
Whisper
    ↓
Text
    ↓
Gemini
    ↓
Response text
    ↓
ElevenLabs
    ↓
Speech
    ↓
Speaker
This is basically the architecture of a voice assistant like JARVIS.
For your project, I'd install:
pip install google-genai openai-whisper elevenlabs sounddevice soundfile numpy
and only install pyaudio if you specifically need it.

#pyhton 
The with ... as statement in Python is used to manage resources automatically.
The idea is:
Open something → use it → automatically clean it up when you're done.

#RAG: retrival augmented generation:-
RAG is a technology used to train anything to get better realtime outputs based on the pervious conversation 
benifits of RAG : 1. reduce hellucination 2. always keep knowledge upto date 3.cost effective(keep it very easy to train the model) 4. Maintain the data privacy
RAG have two main components used 
1. injection pipeline
  it is basically a process like:
  PDFs, different data-> Extract data -> splite into chunks -> chunks of text( compressed text) ->  using embedding API -> convert to vectors -> store embedding into semantic indexs [chromaDB] (we basically store embeddings and doc chunks) -> this becomes our knowledge base
2. retrival pipeline